title: For Sale/Trade:  Type 38 Arisaka w/ Bayonet, Sling, and Ammo
postcontent:
Up for sale or trade is my Type 38 Arisaka.

The rifle:
The Mum has been ground off, like 90%+ of Arisakas.
It is a Type 38, Series 24 from the Kukora Arsenal.

The wood on the stock is rougher, admittedally, but has never been sporterized, sanded, refinished, or repaired.  All original piece of WWII history.

The bluing on the rifle is in very good shape with no rust.  And the bore is surprisingly bright with 4 deep grooves.  It also has good headspace with no deformations in the brass.

The Bayonet:  It was made by Toyoda Automatic Loom.  The Toyoda Automatic Loom company would become Toyota.  The bluing on the blade is immaculate.  No rust or pitting.  The only marks on the blade are from where it is inserted into the scabbard, which comes with it.  It would be difficult to find another Arisaka bayonet in this condition, let alone another Toyoda in this shape.  Has the factory sharp, about half of the blade.

The Sling:  This sling is an ORIGINAL leather Arisaka Sling.  It is dark brown/black leather that has a good bit of wear.  There is a slight tear in one spot.  The kicker is the Japanese characters painted on the inside of the sling.  I do not know the meaning, but it looks like it was done be a Japanese soldier in the field.  You rarely find an original Arisaka Sling.

I also have 20 rounds of new manufactured 6.5 Jap ammo, sealed.

I am more looking to trade than sell, but make me a cash offer, I'll consider it.
I'd take $400 obo. Don't be afraid to offer.  All reasonable offers considered.

Just email me, and I'll respond to every offer. The worst I can say is "No Thanks"
If the ad is still up, I still have, so please no "Do you still have it" emails. Just send your offer.

This weapon blonged to my father and was well cared for up until he passed away.

Ruger Model 10/22 Carbine .22 long rifle for sale.  This weapon is in near perfect condition as the pictures reveal.  There are 4-6 very light scratches/dents in the wooden stock. From what I understand, this model is one of the civilian versions of the Mini 14 Carbine.  The scope and rings are cheapos and the scope will not adjust magnification easily. With this weapon, I am providing an additional 1,425 rounds.  Also included is the leather sling pictured.  The sling is in very good condition. postcontent:
I picked this up at a gun show.  Upon investigation, I found that Hopkins & Allen was one of the names that Merwin Hulbert produced pistols.  According to the 2011 Standard Catalog of Firearms this is officially called the Double-Action Pocket Model, small frame with folding hammer.  The finish on this one will be 90+%.  I have found the serial number "885" on butt, the cylinder, the ejecting star, the frame under the grip and on the underside of the right grip panel handwritten in some sort of white marking medium.

This weapon was from the era of black gun powder, it would not be safe to fire modern ammo.

Going back to the above mentioned book, this pistol in its condition would fall into the "Very Good" description valued at $800.
